On August 12, 2009, President Obama awarded 16 individuals the 2009 Presidential Medal of Freedom. The recipients included Nancy Goodman Brinker, who founded Susan G. Komen for the Cure to challenge stigmas and support breast cancer research; Dr. Pedro José "Joe" Greer, Jr., who founded the Camillus Health Concern to provide medical services for the uninsured; Stephen Hawking, who made significant contributions to scientific discoveries and inspired people worldwide; Jack French Kemp, a football player and public servant who advocated for his beliefs with integrity; Senator Edward M. Kennedy, who fought for equal opportunity and justice for all Americans; Billie Jean Moffitt King, a tennis player and advocate for gender equality; Reverend Joseph E. Lowery, a civil rights leader who championed nonviolence and social justice; Dr. Joseph Medicine Crow – High Bird, a member of the Crow tribe who served in World War II and contributed to cultural and historical preservation; Harvey Bernard Milk, one of the first openly gay elected officials who fought discrimination with courage and conviction; Sandra Day O'Connor, the first woman on the United States Supreme Court; Sidney Poitier, an actor who advanced the Nation's dialogue on race and respect; Chita Rivera, a Broadway performer who broke barriers and inspired women; Mary Robinson, a crusader for women's rights and human rights around the world; Dr. Janet Davison Rowley, a scientist who identified chromosomal abnormalities as the cause of leukemia and other cancers; Archbishop Emeritus Desmond Mpilo Tutu, who played a significant role in South Africa's history and continues to advocate for justice and humanity; and Professor Muhammad Yunus, who revolutionized banking to help lift people out of poverty. These individuals were honored for their remarkable contributions to various fields and their impact on society.